I was born in Cameroon in Central Africa. I’ve been in the US for three years. I came with my whole family—my dad wanted us to have education here. It’s been easy in a certain way, but sometimes I discover certain realities, how racism is a really big thing in this country. I walk on the street and I look like an African American, not an actual African. One time I was just walking on the street and I got handcuffed by police. I was just going to the bakery to buy some cakes. I was actually eating my cake on the street and I saw the police officers parking their cars and I even saw helicopters and those lights, and they parked their car next to me and handcuffed me. They started asking me questions, whether I was fighting or not. I told them I went out to buy a cake. Then I heard on their radio one of his co-workers saying that the person who was in the fight was not a black person so they let me go. It was the craziest experience I ever had. Being American only means opportunities. It doesn’t mean being at the top of the world or being great, it just means having the opportunity to do something great. You come here, you get educated, you don’t forget about your culture and where you’re from, you know your goals, and you should try to make other parts of the world and even here a better place. I think what’s happening right now is very sad. People don't leave their country because they want to leave their country; many people leave their country because they are in trouble. We are in the same world and should be looking for the good of all people, not only our people. I always hated that word, “undocumented.” They should not be considered “undocumented,” they should just be considered as people because we all live in the same world, we all live on earth. Earth belongs to all of us.

Smalling on Valencia

It’s officially awards season and United’s annual ceremony is being held tomorrow night.

Smalling has been explaining why he has voted for Valencia to win player of the season.

Speaking to MUTV he said: “There were two players I thought of voting for. Zlatan, because he’s been our talisman this season, the one scoring the goals. But I actually voted for Antonio. “I think Antonio has been so consistent, at times he’s been our outlet, whether he’s been playing at right-back or on the right wing. He’s been so dependable as well, not just in an attacking sense, but also when he’s been defending. Any winger or striker that comes up against him has to get around him. That means they have to be stronger or quicker than him, and neither of those is easy!”

اسمالينگ از والنسيا مي گويد
فصل رسمي جوايز فرارسيده و مراسم جوايز سالانه منچستريونايتد فردا شب برگزار خواهد شد.
كريس اسمالينگ هم درباره علت راي دادنش به "آنتونيو والنسيا" براي عنوان "بهترين بازيكن فصل" توضيح مي دهد.
او در مصاحبه با كانال منچستريونايتد گفت:
"در واقع دو بازيكن بودند كه راي دادن به آنها را مدنظر داشتم، زلاتان، چراكه در اين فصل تعويذ خوش شانسي ما بوده، كسي كه گل ها را به ثمر مي رساند، اما در آخر به آنتونيو راي دادم."
"به عقيده من او امسال سطح عملكرد ثابتي داشته است. در مقاطعي از فصل، او راه خروج ما از مخمصه بوده است؛ چه در دفاع چپ و چه در بال چپ. او همچنين خيلي قابل اتكا نشان داده است، نه فقط در فاز هجومي، بلكه حتي وقتي در حال دفاع كردن بوده است. هر وينگر يا مهاجمي كه در برابر او قرار بگيرد، براي رد شدن از او يا بايد قوي تر و يا سريع تر از او باشد، و هيچ كدام از اين دو كار آساني نيست!"
